---
title: CSS QR Code
description: A decorative QR-like pattern drawn with CSS `box-shadow` on a single element — no images, no SVG, no JS.
slug: qr-code
cssFile: qr-code.css
explanation: "CSS `box-shadow` accepts an unlimited list of shadows, each an independent colored rectangle offset from the element. With `blur: 0` and `spread: 0`, each shadow is the exact same size as the element — a sharp pixel. By positioning one `10×10px` element at the top-left and casting shadows at multiples of 12px (10px cell + 2px gap), you can paint an entire pixel grid with a single HTML element."
---
{% extends "example.njk" %}
{% block demo %}
<div class="demo-qr-code">
	<div class="qr-wrap">
		<div class="qr-pixel"></div>
		<span class="qr-label">purecss.com</span>
	</div>
	<p class="qr-caption">One `&lt;div&gt;` — all pixels are CSS `box-shadow` values</p>
</div>
{% endblock %}

{% block html_code %}
{%- highlight "html" %}
<!-- entire QR grid = one element -->
<div class="qr-pixel"></div>
{%- endhighlight %}
{% endblock %}

{% block css_code %}
{%- highlight "css" %}
.qr-pixel {
  width: 10px;
  height: 10px;
  background: #1a1a1a; /* cell (1,1) */
  box-shadow:
    /* each value = one 10×10 pixel cell */
    /* x y blur spread color */
    10px 0 0 0 #1a1a1a,  /* (1,2) */
    20px 0 0 0 #1a1a1a,  /* (1,3) */
    /* ... 50+ more cells ... */
    80px 80px 0 0 #1a1a1a; /* (9,9) */
}
{%- endhighlight %}
{% endblock %}
